## Pre-Warming Pattern

Eagerly compute `@cached_property` values during the sequential snapshot phase
so they're already in `instance.__dict__` before render threads access them.
This eliminates the race entirely — no concurrent computation, no wasted work.

```python
# In snapshot phase (sequential, before parallel render):
def pre_warm_for_render(site: Site) -> None:
    """Touch @cached_property values to populate __dict__ before parallel render."""
    for section in site.sections:
        _ = section.sorted_pages
        _ = section.sorted_subsections
        _ = section.subsection_index_urls
        _ = section.regular_pages
    for page in site.pages:
        _ = page.visibility
        _ = page.authors
```

Pre-warming is the right choice when:
- The property does I/O (disk, network) — avoids duplicate work
- The property is on a shared object (Section) — eliminates race window
- The computation is expensive — avoids N threads computing the same thing

Pre-warming is unnecessary when:
- The property returns an immutable type — race is already benign
- The property is on Page and only accessed by the owning render thread

